In article <1s3afe$qs9@kyle.eitech.com>, ekr@kyle.eitech.com (Eric Rescorla) writes:
|> In article <1s38lo$8oe@tuegate.tue.nl> johan@blade.stack.urc.tue.nl (Johan Wevers) writes:
|> >Mark A Allyn writes:
|> >> The question that I have is why can't someone take one of these chips
|> >> and reverse engineer it? I mean, take the thing to a chip testing/
|> >> analysis facility, one with a decent electron microscope. Just pry
|> >> off the top of the chip and start scanning it with the electron
|> >> microcope and figure out the circuitry.
|> >
|> >I think reverse engeneering with this method is impossibe. To start, an
|> >electron microscope can only see the surface. Most modern IC's have a
|> >3-dimensional structure which cannot be determined by scanning the surface.
|> >Further, electron microscopes can only see things which are electrically
|> >conductive.
|> This doesn't sound right. Why should, say, a TEM, have trouble
|> seeing nonconductive stuff? Maybe you're thinking of an STM?
|> (Although I'm not sure that's true either).

The problem is it is not possible to tell what parts of the
silicon have received doping to make them conductive.

